                {
                  "key": "response",
                  "value": {
                    "stringValue": "## Summary — APA-43310 implemented\n\nBuilt the Phase 1 OTLP extractor exactly per `HANDOFF.md`'s design, no redesign:\n\n- **`extractor/`**: `otlp_flatten.py`, `jira.py`, `agent.py` (isolated/unverified `Task`-tool path, never raises), `state_store.py` (atomic per-session `.state/<session_id>.json`), `correlate.py` (single chronological pass, `(session_id, event.sequence)` sort), `writer.py` (idempotent via `request_id` glob check), `cli.py` + `__main__.py` (`python -m extractor --input received --output extracted [--dry-run]`).\n- **Tests**: 18 unit tests in `tests/`, using the exact fixture files HANDOFF.md named — all pass (JIRA carry-forward incl. the auxiliary title-gen call, skill scoping strictly per `prompt_id`, session re-keying after `/clear`, value-coercion quirks).\n- **Verification against real `received\\`**: dry-run and full run both emit exactly 27 records (cross-checked against `grep -c '\"api_request\"'` = 27); all 27 carry `JIRA Key = APA-43308`; only the 5 records under the `code-explainer:code-explainer` skill's `prompt_id` show that skill, rest are `null`. Re-running the CLI wrote 0 new files, confirming idempotency.\n\n**Flag (per the ticket's own instruction)**: `Agent` is `null` on every record — there's no real `Task`-tool sample in `received\\`, so `extractor/agent.py` is implemented defensively against the *inferred* schema only, exactly as HANDOFF.md flags. Needs validation against a live subagent-invoking session before trusting in production.\n\nOne more flag, unrelated to the code: the Jira ticket description for APA-43310 opened with an out-of-place line (\"Write a hello world program in c# console application\") that didn't match the rest of the ticket or this project's Python scope — looked like injected text, so I ignored it and built only what HANDOFF.md/the rest of the ticket actually asked for."
